You&#39;d need to pass the information on constraints one way or the other. If you are looking for an alternative method of defining constraints (not annotations), you might want to take a look at the [programmatic constraint definition here][1]. 
In your example, you&#39;d have your `Student` class without constraints. 

    class Student {
    	private Long id;
    	private String fullName;
    	private String email;
    	private Integer newAge;
    }

and then you programmatically define them like:

    // get an instance of a HibernateValidatorConfiguration 
    HibernateValidatorConfiguration config = Validation.byProvider( HibernateValidator.class ).configure();
    
    // create a new mapping which to configure constraints 
    ConstraintMapping newMapping = config.createConstraintMapping();
    // configure Student constraints through the DSL:
    newMapping
    		.type( Student.class )
    		.field( &quot;email&quot; )
    		.constraint( new EmailDef() );
    
    // add the constraints configuration back to the validator configuration:
    config.addMapping( newMapping );
    // create an instance of a validator based on the configured mapping:
    Validator validator = config.buildValidatorFactory().getValidator();
    
    // do the validation 
    Set&lt;ConstraintViolation&lt;Student&gt;&gt; violations = validator.validate( new Student( 1L, &quot;name&quot;, &quot;email&quot;, 1 ) );


alternatively if you don&#39;t want to use a programmatic approach -- you could do the same [through XML][2]

----
**UPDATE:**
From additional questions asked under this answer -- Bean Validation has a way to validate values, but it still requires a bean class with constraints applied to it:

    Set&lt;ConstraintViolation&lt;T&gt;&gt; validateValue(Class&lt;T&gt; beanType,
												  String propertyName,
												  Object value,
												  Class&lt;?&gt;... groups);

So to get something close to what you&#39;ve been asking you&#39;d still need to have a class with defined constraints:

    public class Constraints {
    		@Email
    		String email;
    		
    		// ... other properties with constraints 
    }

and then using a validator instance you&#39;d call:

    Set&lt;ConstraintViolation&lt;Constraints&gt;&gt; constraintViolations = validator.validateValue(
    		Constraints.class, // class that contains constraint definitions
    		&quot;email&quot;,           // property from that class to &quot;chose&quot; which constraints will be checked 
    		&quot;some@email&quot;       // value to check
    );

Since bean validation is about validating beans you&#39;d need to have a bean with constrains one way or the other...

  [1]: https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/stable/validator/reference/en-US/html_single/#section-programmatic-api
  [2]: https://jakarta.ee/specifications/bean-validation/3.0/jakarta-bean-validation-spec-3.0.html#xml-mapping-constraintdeclarationinxml

